Goal¶

Provide investors with a macro analysis about energy consumption trends to make informed decisions when investing in the energy sector.

Audience¶

Our audience is investors looking to put money into the energy sector.

Questions¶

Factors to consider when investing in the renewable energy sector:

  1. What is the trend of renewable consumption in North America over time?

    • This will provide an investor with market confidence if the renewable energy consumption trends are on the rise over the past few decades.

  2. How does the price of oil impact renewable energy consumption?

    • It is important to see the impact of oil since it is the most consumed energy type in North America.

  3. Why should an investor consider investing in renewable energy in North America?

    • This will be answered by trends of renewable enrgy investment and a solar module cost analysis. Investors want to know the landscape of who else is investing and how much one can profit from the priciple investment.

Data Sets¶

  1. BP Statistical Review of all energy resources
  2. World Bank Population
  3. UN Population
  4. International Energy Agency (IEA) via World Bank
  5. Bloomberg New Energy Finance

Section Overview¶

Each section will begin with a brief discussion of the clean/analysis process and the analysis conclusion. Then, the code and graphs are provided in there own section with approriate headers.

Data Cleaning¶

The data sets are cleaned to provide a compact dataframe from which relevant data can be chosen for further analysis.

The data sets cleaned were:

  1. Energy Consumption data
  2. Population data
  3. Coal and Oil Price

Energy Consumption Cleaning¶

Analysis of 'NaN'¶

The "NaN" values we had were mostly for renewable energy consumption in the early years(~1960-1970). We replaced the NaN with zeros because the region/country either:

  1. Did not record renewable energy usage
  2. Did not use renewable enrgy at that time

We restricted our analysis to the years where there was the fewest NaN's.

Procedure¶

  1. Read the raw excel file.
  2. Select the required regions, which had the string 'Total'. We only want to analyze total regions and NOT country-by-country.
  3. Select the data only for the last 20 years. We have data from 1960's to 2000's. However, much of the renewable data is not given for the 1960's and 1970's. We will be analyzing a subset of our data.
  4. Select the data which had the string 'Other'. The other column has unknown countries added together. We want to know the countries we are working on to be as specific as possible.
  5. Subtracted the step 4 (the 'Others' column) data from the corresponding step 2 (the main regions 'Total' column) data. This is done to eliminate the unknown countries.
  6. Finally the columns and the indices are renamed appropriately.

Population Data¶

Procedure¶

We have two different data sets for population, one from the "World Bank" and the other from the "UN".

Our aim is to calculate the energy consumptions per capita for which we need to divide the above dataframe by the population dataframe. We use the two data sets as not one have all the countries and regions we require. So the regions are very carefully selected from each

Steps taken:

  1. Read the raw dataframes
  2. Select the data of the relevant countries corresponding to the energy consumption dataframe.
  3. Select the total world, OECD countries and Non-OECD countries' population data
  4. Get a final dataframe with the each regions's population corresponding to the energy consumption dataframe.

In statistics, 'per capita' is used to compare the economic indicators of countries with different population sizes. Per capita divides a statistical measurement for an organization by its population. The equation is $\frac{measurement}{per~capita} = measure~per~capita$. This creates a data set that provides a stronger regional or country-wise comparison of the energy consumption data.

Data Distribution¶

Histograms and Kernal Density Estimation¶

A frequency distribution shows how often each different value in a set of data occurs. We are looking to see if our data is normally distributed. In a normal or "typical" distribution, points are as likely to occur on one side of the average as on the other. Note that other distributions look similar to the normal distribution. We will answer the normal distribution question via histograms, kernal density estimations, and quantile-quantile plots.

One of the issues with using a histogram as a density estimator is that the choice of bin size and location can lead to representations that have qualitatively different features. A kernal density estimation can smooth a histogram to see a distribution of the data. The free parameters of kernel density estimation are the kernel, which specifies the shape of the distribution placed at each point, and the kernel bandwidth, which controls the size of the kernel at each point.

Remember, this is all to get an initial glimpse at the distribution of our data. We need the distribution type to decide on statistical tests.

Bin Size¶

Sturge’s rule is one way to choose bin sizes.

$K=1+3.322~log(N)$

$K$ is the number of needed bins and $N$ is the number of observations. Using the data.describe() we can calculate bin sizes. The count is 21 which is used for our N value. $K=1+3.322~log(21) \approx 5.39$, which is $\approx 5$. So we decided on 5 bins for our histograms.

Mean and Median¶

We also looked at the mean and median of each variable. If the means are close to the medians, this would indicate a normal distribution.

Quantile-Quantile Plot¶

Another popular plot for checking the distribution of a data sample is the quantile-quantile plot or QQ plot for short.

This plot generates its own sample of the idealized distribution that we are comparing with, in this case the Gaussian distribution. The idealized samples are divided into groups (e.g. 5), called quantiles. Each data point in the sample is paired with a similar member from the idealized distribution at the same cumulative distribution.

The resulting points are plotted as a scatter plot with the idealized value on the x-axis and the data sample on the y-axis.

A perfect match for the distribution will be shown by a line of dots on a 45-degree angle from the bottom left of the plot to the top right. Often a line is drawn on the plot to help make this expectation clear. Deviations by the dots from the line shows a deviation from the expected distribution.

Conclusion of Distribution¶

The histograms/kde plots make the data appear as if it is not normally distributed. However, the means and medians of the data and the Q-Q plots would indicate:

Normally Distributed

  1. Hydroelectric Consumption
  2. Wind Consumption
  3. Total Renewable Energy Consumption

Not Normally Distributed

  1. Solar Consumption
  2. Oil Consumption

Data Analysis¶

Percentage of energy consumption by type of energy¶

The pie chart shows the percentages of energy consumption in North America. This illustrates that the energy market is predominantly nonrenewable energy sources. Oil, gas, and coal dominate the market.

Time Series of Renewable Energy Consumption¶

This illustrates that hydroelectricity has remained fairly consistent over a 25 year period. Solar and Wind consumption has an increase in consumption since 2005. This is a good indicator for investors looking to put their money in the renewable energy sector.

Linear Regressions & Correlations¶

We used a ordinary linear regression and plotted a correlation for:

  1. Oil Price and Hydroelectricity Consumption
  2. Oil Price and Solar Consumption
  3. Oil Price and Wind Consumption
  4. Oil Price and Total Renewable Energy Consumption

We wanted to see if the price of oil affected the renewable resources. A linear regression and correlation would show this relationship. This is important because oil is the leading enegy type consumed by North America. Also, we conducted a Kendall tau correlation test on solar energy consumption since it was not normally distributed. Kendall Rank Correlation assess statistical associations based on the ranks of the data. Kendall rank correlation (non-parametric) is an alternative to Pearson’s correlation (parametric) when the data you’re working with has failed one or more assumptions of the test.

None of our renewable variables appear to have a strong linear correlation with the price of oil. The orginial Solar data appears correlated in Kendall tau test,then we found the first half of Solar consumption is keeping increase but stay near zero. Then we test the second half of solar consumption, there are not correlated in Kendall tau test. This is good news for our investors. This means that one can invest in renewable energy without worry of the change of price of oil in long term(assuming our analysis is correct).

What regions/countries are investmenting in renewable energies?¶

The time series plot of how much each region is investing in renewable resources. The second graph is a bar plot of renewable energy investment, per country, as a percentage of GDP. These graphs are two different ways to look at how the world, by region, then, by country, is investing in renewable resources. One important question any investor will ask is: "Is there room for growth in a market?" One should notice that United States appears to invest a large amount in renewable energy. However, looking at the second graph (renewable energy investment as a percentage of GDP), one will notice that the United States invest the least relative to the other countries. Therefore, the United States' renewable energy sector has much room to grow. A 2019 article on the website www.thebalance.com arrives at the same conclusion that the U.S. has much room for growth in the renewable energy sector.

Solar Module Cost¶

Another reason to invest in renewable energy is because the cost of materials to produce renewable energy has decreased. Therefore, the return will be greater. Solar energy is an example of the lowering cost of renewable energy components. The cost of the photovaltaic modules has decreased and the modules today produce more energy per module than they did in the 1980's.

Conclusion¶

When deciding which companies to invest in, investors look at the trends as well as profitability in that sector.

Questions Answered in this analysis:¶

  1. What is the trend of renewable consumption in North America over time?

    • Renewable energy consumption has been continuously increasing over time in North America, though it is still a very small percentage of GDP.

  2. How does the price of oil impact renewable energy consumption?

    • As we showed, renewable energy consumption is not affected by oil prices, which is known to be volatile. Therefore, investors do not have to worry that oil prices will hinder their renewable energy investment.

  3. Why should an investor consider investing in renewable energy in North America?

    • Costs in the renewable energy sector, such as solar panels, have been decreasing over time. This shows a high potential for profits, especially in North America where renewable energy investment is such a small percentage of GDP.
